    <div class="card">
        <h2>Understanding Nuclear Fusion Stocks</h2>
        <p>Nuclear fusion represents the Holy Grail of clean energy. Unlike fission, which splits atoms and creates radioactive waste, fusion combines light atoms (like hydrogen) to release massive amounts of energy—mimicking the exact process that powers our sun. While commercial viability has historically been decades away, recent breakthroughs in magnetic confinement and laser ignition have dramatically accelerated timelines.</p>
        <p>For everyday investors, the landscape of nuclear fusion stocks is complex. There are currently no publicly traded pure-play fusion companies available on major exchanges. Most cutting-edge fusion startups—like Commonwealth Fusion Systems or TAE Technologies—remain privately held, backed by billionaires and venture capital firms. However, that doesn't mean retail investors are entirely locked out of the sector.</p>
        <p>To gain exposure, investors must look at the broader supply chain and ancillary beneficiaries. This includes massive energy conglomerates exploring advanced nuclear technologies, specialized engineering firms building reactor components, and materials companies supplying essential resources like superconducting magnets or specialized isotopes. Think of it as selling the picks and shovels during a gold rush.</p>
    </div>

